      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "5e820262f281a977",
      "text": "Wars are systems of interaction and communication that are about relationship definitions. And they only end when the partners involved agree that they are over. This is generally the case when one party capitulates and defines itself as the loser. Thus, the paradoxical situation arises in which the weaker party determines whether the stronger party is the winner. "
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "0af47be6e970f772",
      "text": "The supposed superior can only enforce this definition of relationship if he is actually able to destroy the opponent. This can be the case in dueling situations, where two people face each other eye to eye. One of the opponents can kill the other, which seals his victory. The same applies to the traditional war between nations, where governments are legitimized to declare the surrender of their country."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "3ecbb01bd40a510b",
      "text": "In general, both parties have the right to veto the peace."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "05a2bfb07aeca278",
      "text": "Since annihilation or surrender defines the end of war, wars can only end when you are dealing with an opponent who can be destroyed. If it is a community that is not defined territorially or by individual survival, but ideally, there are no \"final solutions\"."
    },
    {
      "type": "paragraph",
      "id": "7e394688f7f09f9d",
      "text": "It is enough if someone remembers the identity-forming ideas or values - after a long time, perhaps - to reanimate the respective social unit and let it arise again. That is why, even after more than 70 years of Soviet rule, the churches in Russia have come back to life in a very short time. And this is also why wars have been going on for centuries in the Balkans, even if no one remembers their beginnings."
    },
